{"key":"processedPost-13163960","value":{"id":13163960,"first":13158546,"last":13192545,"when":1283954594,"utime":"09/08/10 05:03 PM","cleanedPost":"Nibin gave the best answer, but I should add that sterilization is never 100% complete with grains.&nbsp; In addition, filters on bags and/or jars are never 100% effective.&nbsp; A 99.99% filter will still let that .001% of bacteria in the air get through, and if you sleep in the room, have dogs and cats, run a vacuum cleaner, etc., there's a LOT of bacteria in the air.<br />With dry grains, you give the mycelium the advantage and it can colonize before the less favored competitors.&nbsp; Mycelium won't colonize the wet grains at the bottom of the jars, which leaves the spot perfectly suited for bacteria.<br />RR"}}